top.name: aws
top.description: Lifecycle management of AWS resources, including  EC2, Lambda, EKS, ECS, VPC, S3, RDS, DynamoDB, and more. This provider is maintained internally by the HashiCorp AWS Provider team.

top.name: random
top.description: Supports the use of randomness within Terraform configurations. This is a logical provider, which means that it works entirely within Terraform logic, and does not interact with any other services.

top.name: google
top.description: Lifecycle management of GCP resources, including Compute Engine, Cloud Storage, Cloud SDK, Cloud SQL, GKE, BigQuery, Cloud Functions and more. This provider is collaboratively maintained by the Google Terraform Team at Google and the Terraform team at HashiCorp

top.name: null
top.description: Provides constructs that intentionally do nothing – useful in various situations to help orchestrate tricky behavior or work around limitations.

top.name: azurerm
top.description: Lifecycle management of Microsoft Azure using the Azure Resource Manager APIs. maintained by the Azure team at Microsoft and the Terraform team at HashiCorp

top.name: kubernetes
top.description: Management of all Kubernetes resources, including Deployments, Services, Custom Resources (CRs and CRDs), Policies, Quotas and more.

top.name: time
top.description: Used to interact with time-based resources. The provider itself has no configuration options.

top.name: local
top.description: Used to manage local resources, such as creating files

top.name: external
top.description: A special provider that exists to provide an interface between Terraform and external programs – useful for integrating Terraform with a system for which a first-class provider does not exist.

top.name: tls
top.description: Provides utilities for working with Transport Layer Security keys and certificates. It provides resources that allow private keys, certificates and certficate requests to be created as part of a Terraform deployment.

top.name: vault
top.description: Allows Terraform to read from, write to, and configure Hashicorp Vault.

top.name: azuread
top.description: Manage users, groups, service principals, and applications in Azure Active Directory using the Microsoft Graph API. This provider is maintained by the Azure providers team at HashiCorp.

top.name: archive
top.description: The archive provider exposes resources to manage archive files.

top.name: helm
top.description: Manage installed Charts in your Kubernetes cluster, in the same way Helm does, through Terraform

top.name: template
top.description: This provider has been archived. Please use the `templatefile` function or the `Cloudinit` provider instead. See documentation for more details.

top.name: http
top.description: Utility provider for interacting with generic HTTP servers as part of a Terraform configuration.

top.name: confluent
top.description: Simplify Apache Kafka Terraform deployment with the Confluent Terraform Provider. Manage Confluent Environments, Kafka Clusters, Kafka Topics, Kafka ACLs, Service Accounts, and more.

top.name: cloudinit
top.description: Exposes the cloudinit_config data source which renders a multipart MIME configuration for use with cloud-init (previously available as the template_cloudinit_config resource in the template provider)

top.name: kubectl
top.description: This provider is the best way of managing Kubernetes resources in Terraform, by allowing you to use the thing Kubernetes loves best - yaml!

top.name: tfe
top.description: Provision Terraform Cloud or Terraform Enterprise - with Terraform! Management of organizations, workspaces, teams, variables, run triggers, policy sets, and more. Maintained by the Terraform Cloud team at HashiCorp.

top.name: dns
top.description: Supports DNS updates (RFC 2136) and can optionally be configured with secret key based transaction authentication (RFC 2845).

top.name: consul
top.description: Exposes resources used to interact with a Consul cluster, such as adding external services or working with the key/value store

top.name: mongodbatlas
top.description: Deploy, update, and manage Atlas configurations as code through Terraform

top.name: awscc
top.description: Lifecycle management of AWS resources powered by the AWS Cloud Control API. This provider is fully generated from the available CloudFormation resource definitions and is maintained internally by the HashiCorp AWS Provider team.

top.name: nomad
top.description: Exposes resources to interact with a HashiCorp Nomad cluster.

top.name: coder
top.description: Coder is a self-hosted remote development platform. Shifting software development from local machines to the cloud. Onboard new developers in minutes, build code on powerful servers—all while keeping source code and data secure and keeping your developers in flow.

top.name: oci
top.description: Interact with the many resources supported by the Oracle Cloud Infrastructure via the OCI provider APIs.

top.name: elasticstack
top.description: Configure and manage Elasticstack components such as Elasticsearch, Kibana and more, as code, on Elastic Cloud or on premises.
